Ques: How do you select which language to use Java, Python and C/C++ ?
Ans: “I choose a language based on system constraints. For high-performance or low-level control, I use C++. For scalable backend systems, I prefer Java due to its mature ecosystem and concurrency support. 
For rapid development or data-heavy tasks, I use Python. In many real-world systems, I combine them—for example, Python for ML, Java for services, and C++ for performance-critical components.”

Ques: How do you select Git provider ?
Ans: select a Git provider based on CI/CD capabilities, security requirements, hosting model, and ecosystem integration. For example, I’d choose GitHub for its developer experience and strong integrations,
GitLab when I need an all-in-one DevOps platform or self-hosting, and Bitbucket when working in an Atlassian ecosystem with Jira. The decision depends on balancing team productivity with enterprise 
requirements.

Ques: How does load configurations work in Spring Boot internally ?
Ans: @EnableAutoConfiguration works by dynamically importing configuration classes based on classpath and conditions.

Internal flow (brief):

It triggers:

@Import(AutoConfigurationImportSelector.class)
AutoConfigurationImportSelector:

Reads auto-config classes from: META-INF/spring/org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.AutoConfiguration.imports
(older versions: spring.factories)

Applies conditions:
@ConditionalOnClass
@ConditionalOnMissingBean
@ConditionalOnProperty
Only matching configurations are loaded as @Configuration classes.
Beans are created, but back off if you already defined your own beans.

It uses AutoConfigurationImportSelector to load predefined configuration classes and conditionally registers beans based on classpath, properties, and existing beans.
